<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-11-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-11-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="277" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d277">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/608½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by Mr. Hugh S. Gibson, Division of Foreign
                                Intelligence, Department of State</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-11-05">
                                    <hi rend="italic">November 5, 1917</hi>
                                </date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>When the Chinese Minister called on the Secretary this morning he was
                            handed copies of the notes exchanged with the Japanese Special
                            Ambassador. The Secretary informed him that China had not been informed
                            in regard to the negotiations in progress because it was felt that if
                            she were informed and made no protest her responsibility would be
                            engaged.</p>
                    </div>
